{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"322dc6f7-e466-4b34-bcd7-1f37a73cc014","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is what you need to bring workloads (like `maui`) in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-installs workloads **at their current versions**. It fixes corrupted installations but won't pull newer versions needed by a newer SDK.\n\n**TL;DR:** SDK changed → versions are mismatched → use `update`. If workloads were already the right version but files were corrupted, that's when you'd use `repair`.\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf issues persist after updating, try `dotnet workload restore` from your project directory — it ensures all workloads referenced in your project file are installed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6023e502-335e-44ba-93cf-2a4cbbea487f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to explore any codebase or run commands.","outputTokens":278,"requestId":"3C24:1E2E16:D34986:106E7E5:6A0128B5"},"id":"cf957d03-374b-41b5-a9bf-b32cb8af768b","timestamp":"2026-05-11T00:54:21.331Z","parentId":"9e2d0f56-6952-4195-b9ab-0c354da7e364"}
